"Barnes E.A., Hartmann D.L.","Testing a theory for the effect of latitude on the persistence of eddy-driven jets using CMIP3 simulations",2010,"Geophysical Research Letters","37","15", L15801,"","",,,10.1029/2010GL044144,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77955481325&partnerID=40&md5=f871fcd7e9697b6ae9228597c1654799","Department of Atmospheric Science, University of Washington, Box 351640, Seattle, WA 98195-1640, United States","Barnes, E.A., Department of Atmospheric Science, University of Washington, Box 351640, Seattle, WA 98195-1640, United States; Hartmann, D.L., Department of Atmospheric Science, University of Washington, Box 351640, Seattle, WA 98195-1640, United States","The effect of latitude on the persistence of north-south shifts in the position of the jet is investigated in 37 CMIP3 integrations over four forcing scenarios. The persistence of the Southern Annular Mode (SAM) decreases when the mean jet is located closer to the pole. An asymmetry is shown whereby the equatorward-shifted jet is more persistent than the poleward-shifted jet. The sphericity of the earth inhibits wave breaking on the poleward flank of the jet which decreases the feedback between the eddies and the mean-flow and yields a wider, less self-sustaining jet. The results suggest a decrease in e-folding time of the SAM of 3 days per degree of poleward shift of the jet. The mechanism described explains why models with jets too far equatorward relative to observations over-predict the timescale of the SAM and suggests that these models will also exaggerate poleward shifts of jets associated with global warming. Copyright 2010 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Oceanography; E-folding; Poleward shift; Southern annular mode; Time-scales; Wavebreaking; Global warming; global warming; numerical model; polar meteorology; sphere; theoretical study; timescale; wave breaking",,,,,,"Barnes, E.A., Hartmann, D.L., Dynamical feedbacks and the persistence of the NAO (2010) J. Atmos. Sci., 67, pp. 851-865; Barnes, E.A., Hartmann, D.L., Dynamical feedbacks of the Southern Annular Mode in winter and summer (2010) J. Atmos. Sci., 67, pp. 2320-2330; Barnes, E.A., Hartmann, D.L., Frierson, D.M.W., Kidston, J., Effect of latitude on the persistence of eddy-driven jets (2010) Geophys. Res. Lett., 37, pp. L11804. , doi:10.1029/2010GL043199; Berbery, E.H., Vera, C.S., Characteristics of the Southern Hemisphere winter storm track with filtered and unfiltered data (1996) J. Atmos. Sci., 53, pp. 468-481; Gerber, E.P., Polvani, L.M., Ancukiewicz, D., Annular mode time scales in the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change Fourth Assessment Report models (2008) Geophys. Res. Lett., 35, pp. L22707. , doi:10.1029/2008GL035712; Hartmann, D.L., The atmospheric general circulation and its variability (2007) J. Meteorol. Soc. Jpn., 85 B, pp. 123-143; Held, I.M., Stationary and quasi-stationary eddies in the extratropical troposphere: Theory (1983) Large-Scale Dynamical Processes in the Atmosphere, pp. 127-168. , edited by B. J. Hoskins and R. P. Pearce Academic, London; Hoskins, B.J., Karoly, D.J., The steady linear response of a spherical atmosphere to thermal and orographic forcing (1981) J. Atmos. Sci., 38, pp. 1179-1196; Kidston, J., Gerber, E.P., Intermodel variability of the poleward shift of the austral jet stream in the CMIP3 integrations linked to biases in 20th century climatology (2010) Geophys. Res. Lett., 37, pp. L09708. , doi:10.1029/2010GL042873; Lee, S., Held, I.M., Baroclinic wave packets in models and observations (1993) J. Atmos. Sci., 50, pp. 1413-1428; Lorenz, D.J., Hartmann, D.L., Eddy-zonal flow feedback in the Southern Hemisphere (2001) J. Atmos. Sci., 58, pp. 3312-3327; Meehl, G.A., Covey, C., Delworth, T., Latif, M., McAvaney, B., Mitchell, J.F.B., Stouffer, R.J., Taylor, K.E., The WRCP CMIP3 multi-model dataset: A new era in climate change research (2007) Bull. Am. Meteorol. Soc., 88, pp. 1383-1394; Robinson, W.A., On the self-maint